<HL>
   Medicine:
   Merck Plans
   Medicaid
   Price Cut
   ----
   By Ron Winslow
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   MRK
</CO>
<IN>
DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<GV>
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Merck &amp; Co. proposed to make its prescription drugs
available at lower prices to Medicaid patients, but it isn't
clear that the plan will deflect federal and state pressure
to force the pharmaceutical industry to bring down drug
costs.
   Drug companies generally have refused to give price breaks
to Medicaid programs even while granting discounts to other
volume buyers. In the face of budget deficits and rising
prescription prices, legislators and health-care officials
are taking steps to control Medicaid spending on drugs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Merck plan could be both a political and marketing
coup for the nation's leading drug company, and it could save
Medicaid programs nationwide a total of $30 million a year,
based on Merck's current sales. "Merck has taken an important
step away from the policies of greed and unfairness that
unfortunately characterize today's drug companies," said Sen.
David Pryor (D., Ark.), who is drafting legislation aimed at
reducing drug costs for Medicaid and Medicare recipients.
   But it is far from certain that Merck's proposal will
placate regulators or lead other companies to offer similar
plans. For one thing, in a number of states, the offer would
be good only if certain restrictions on Merck drugs are
removed.
   In addition, for the proposal to fend off federal and
state efforts to lower drug prices for the poor, other
companies would have to offer similar discount plans -- and
these would be more costly to competitors because they offer
steeper discounts to bulk purchasers than Merck does. Other
drug companies were studying the plan and hadn't any comment.
   The U.S. and the 50 states share the $50 billion annual
cost of providing medical care to the nation's 23 million
eligible poor. About 7% of Medicaid budgets, or $3.5 billion,
pays for prescription drugs, according to Merck. To control
costs, a dozen states, including California, which accounts
for about 10% of the U.S. prescription drug market, have
adopted formularies, or lists of approved drugs that qualify
for Medicaid payment. Doctors treating poor patients must
prescribe medicines from the formularies, or in some states,
seek special authorization to deviate from the list. Such
policies deny the poor access to many medicines available to
the rest of the country, Merck says.
   With Merck's plan, physicians can "prescribe what they
think is best for their poor patients, just as they do for
patients in the general public," said John L. Zabriskie,
president of Merck Sharpe &amp; Dohme, the Rahway, N.J.,
company's U.S. prescription drug unit. Medicaid currently
accounts for 8% to 10% of Merck's estimated $3 billion of
U.S. sales.
   Under the program, states will get the best price Merck
offers to any customeras long as the state doesn't restrict
access to any Merck drugs. "If they limit access to any of
our products, they won't get the best price on any of our
products," Dr. Zabriskie said.
   Merck's biggest discounts, currently offered only to the
Veterans Administration and a few other federal agencies, are
about 7% to 13% less than Merck's regular wholesale prices,
according to industry estimates. That difference is one of
the lowest in the industry, thus savings from the discount
will be modest at best.
   Sanford Lugar, a pharmacist with New Jersey's Medicaid
program, said it was too early to tell how much Merck's plan
would save his state, but it is "a positive step," he said.
   "We're studying it," said Richard Iniguez, a top official
for MediCal, California's Medicaid program. "But of all
companies to present this {type of} proposal, Merck would
have the least to lose. If, for instance, Pfizer were making
this proposal, we'd have a little more interest."
   Many companies give 30% to 50% discounts on some drugs to
the VA, hospitals, health maintenance organizations and other
bulk pharmaceutical buyers, Mr. Iniguez said. For instance,
MediCal pays $27.83 for 30 tablets of Merck's Pepcid, an
ulcer drug, while the VA pays $24.26, about 13% less, says
Victor Walker, a MediCal pharmacist. By contrast, MediCal
pays $54.77 for 100 of SmithKline Beecham PLC's Tagamet ulcer
pills while the VA pays $27.65, a difference of nearly 50%.
   Drug companies haven't extended discounts to the poverty
programs in part because unlike the VA or big hospitals,
Medicaid doesn't take delivery of the medicines. Generally,
the programs reimburse pharmacists who order and dispense the
products. "Most Medicaid programs pay top dollar for their
drugs," says Mr. Iniguez.
   The California Legislature begins hearings this week on
several bills that would change the state's formulary. One
bill has points similar to those in the Merck proposal;
others would strengthen the hand of state officials in
negotiating prices and adding or removing drugs from the
formulary.
   Mr. Iniguez said that while the state uses its formulary
to control costs, drug companies consider the formulary an
important marketing tool for patented drugs and include the
notation "Approved by MediCal" in ads in medical journals.
"The competition to get your product on the formulary can be
quite intense," he said. "It opens up a market well beyond
MediCal."
   Merck's Pepcid is on California's formulary; Mevacor, a
cholesterol-lowering drug, isn't. Under Merck's plan, the
state would get a discount on both drugs as long as it lifted
restrictions against all Merck products. That would mean
California's poor would have easier access to Mevacor and it
probably would boost sales of the drug as well. The plan, Dr.
Zabriskie asserts, "is fair to the patient, to the states and
to us."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900423-0075
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900423-0075.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Insurers Are Cutting Back or Halting
   Sales of Personal Insurance Policies
</HL>
<DATE>
04/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9C
</SO>
<CO>
   XRX AET AIG CI TIC
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Stricter state regulation, heightened competition and
mounting expenses have turned the once-mediocre returns from
selling personal insurance, such as for autos and homes, into
a flood of red ink for many insurers.
   Insurance companies are reassessing their strategies for
this sector of the market. Some are deciding it's best to cut
back, especially on auto insurance, which many insurers see
as their biggest moneyloser. Other companies are deserting
the personal insurance market entirely.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   On Friday, Xerox Corp.'s Crum &amp; Forster Inc. unit became
the latest company to drop out. It announced that it was
terminating its personal insurance business nationwide.
Robert Vairo, Crum &amp; Forster's president and chief executive
officer, said the decision was based on market conditions and
a belief that the business wasn't going to be profitable any
time soon.
   Last year, Crum &amp; Forster paid out $1.29 in claims and
expenses for every dollar of premium collected in all its
personal lines. That's far worse than the industry average.
Three-quarters of Crum &amp; Forster's personal insurance
business was done in such states as California, New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Florida, Texas and Connecticut, where insurance
regulation is in the midst of being revamped.
   "The public and the regulators can't ask us to pay for
insurance that has been mandated by the state and not be able
to recover those costs and make a reasonable profit," Mr.
Vairo said.
   In recent months, other insurers have taken action.
   Aetna Life &amp; Casualty Co. plans to cut back its auto
insurance business 15% to 20% in states where it's
unprofitable. It will trim agents' auto insurance commissions
to 10% from 15% starting in July, and it has let go some
agents in California. For now, the Hartford, Conn., insurer
said its cutbacks are limited to individual auto insurance.
   Last month, Philadelphia-based Cigna Corp. told agents it
will no longer accept new auto and personal excess liability
policies after May 1 and asked agents to place renewals with
other carriers.
   New Hampshire Insurance Co., a unit of New York-based
American International Group Inc., has accelerated its
withdrawal from the personal lines market and expects to be
out almost entirely by year end.
   Travelers Corp., also based in Hartford, no longer sells
auto insurance in California, where it had a significant
share of the market, and it's selectively cutting back on its
personal lines business in other states. The company is also
streamlining its entire personal insurance operations,
eliminating 500 to 600 jobs in over 90 field offices
throughout the country.
   Analysts believe more companies will take similar steps.
For consumers, such moves mean they will find fewer companies
willing to insure their cars or homes, especially in states
where insurance reforms have been passed or where new
regulation is on the ballot.
   William Yankus at Conning &amp; Co., a research firm, believes
the beginning of a major structural change is taking place in
the personal insurance market. First, the standard companies
drop out of the market. Then, the substandard insurers expand
their business.
   These companies are willing to insure most motorists,
regardless of their driving records, but they charge dearly
for the service. Regulators could be forced to provide
alternatives, such as state-run pools. Mr. Yankus believes it
could be 10 to 15 years before the market corrects as tort
reform and good no-fault laws come into place.
   Besides what insurers consider an unfavorable regulatory
environment, the very nature of the personal insurance
business leaves little room for fat profit margins. Insurers
are offering generally homogenous products in a highly
competitive market. The direct writers, insurers such as
State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Co., Nationwide Mutual
Insurance Co. and B.A.T Industries PLC's Farmers Group Inc.
unit, which employ their own platoons of agents, have lower
commission costs and thus have an edge over the agency
companies, such as Aetna, Cigna and Travelers, which rely on
independent agents. The agency companies have been slowly
losing market share to the direct writers in the last decade.
   Although Crum &amp; Forster's action was spurred by market
forces, analysts believe a recent management change also
might have played a role in the company's move.
   Alan Henderson of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
believes Stuart B. Ross, the newly appointed head of Xerox's
financial-services group, has been asked by top management to
improve the cash flow and profitability of his unit. Dropping
some unprofitable insurance lines and shrinking the entire
financial-services operations are likely moves, Mr. Henderson
said. But despite recent speculation, he doesn't believe
Stamford, Conn.-based Xerox will sell its financial-services
businesses.
   ---
   Laurence Hooper contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900423-0074
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900423-0074.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Torchmark Gets
   Texas Warning
   On Proxy Fight
   ----
   By Michael Allen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9A
</SO>
<CO>
   AGC TMK
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   The Texas State Board of Insurance staff informed
Torchmark Corp. that its proxy fight against American General
Corp. may violate state law, but Torchmark vowed to proceed,
anyway.
   In a letter, the deputy commissioner of the board's legal
and compliance section warned Torchmark that the board will
consider the Birmingham, Ala., insurer to have obtained
"control" of American General if it acquires at American
General's annual meeting on May 2, proxies representing 10%
or more of the power to vote.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under Texas state law, a company must obtain permission
from the insurance commissioner before acquiring control of a
Texas insurance company. Torchmark hasn't sought such
permission.
   Torchmark, which launched its proxy battle after dropping
an unsolicited $50-a-share, or $6.3 billion, offer for its
much-bigger rival, had argued that the vote solicitation
wouldn't lead to control because it was merely attempting to
place five "independent" directors on American General's
15-member board.
   Noting that it has the right to appeal the decision to the
Texas insurance commissioner under two sections of state law,
Torchmark said it intends to pursue, if necessary, one of
those alternatives "at the appropriate time."
   "We believe that it is wrong for American General to spend
time and money in an attempt to deny their shareholders the
opportunity to vote for the independent nominees," Torchmark
said. "We, however, fully intend to continue with our proxy
solicitation."
   The Houston insurer, meanwhile, criticized Torchmark for
failing to clear its nomination with state regulators, who
are charged with protecting the interests of policyholders.
"We believe that the process that the state regulators are
pursuing in order to determine whether to grant approval will
also provide both regulators and policyholders an opportunity
to understand Torchmark's intentions," American General said.
   The Texas decision represents the latest round in a
bruising regulatory fight being waged in almost a dozen
states where American General has subsidiaries. So far,
regulators in California and Virginia have declined to block
the proxy solicitation, while authorities in Tennessee and
New York have warned Torchmark that they consider the
solicitation an attempt to obtain control of American General
without obtaining required approvals.
   The two insurance companies have also battled in federal
court. A U.S. district judge in Houston initially blocked
Torchmark from nominating its five directors, but the
decision was overturned by a federal appeals court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
