<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
04/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   A U.S. HOSTAGE WAS RELEASED by pro-Iranian kidnappers in
Lebanon.
   After nearly 39 months in captivity, educator Robert
Polhill was freed in Beirut by Islamic Jihad for the
Liberation of Palestine, a group that holds at least two
other Americans. Polhill, who was taken to Syria before
heading to West Germany, was the first American captive to be
released in almost three-and-a-half years. The 55-year-old
New Yorker said he was "happy and grateful" about his
release, but expressed concern about those still held. Bush
thanked Syria and Iran for their roles in winning Polhill's
freedom, and called for the release of all hostages.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The terms of Polhill's release, which followed a series of
communiques from the extremists, weren't known. At least 17
foreigners are missing in Lebanon.
   ---
   MILLIONS OF PEOPLE MARKED Earth Day with rallies around
the globe.
   An estimated 200 million people in 140 nations on all
seven continents joined events dedicated to preserving the
environment. More than 3,600 U.S. communities staged programs
to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the Earth Day
anti-pollution movement, cleaning beaches and planting trees.
About 100,000 people gathered in Washington to hear
environmental activists, and thousands watched a balloon
decorated as the Earth rise in New York City.
   Bush expressed support for a tanker-free zone off
Florida's coast and indicated that a decision on offshore oil
drilling would be made "very soon."
   ---
   A Communist official in Moscow warned that Lithuania's
independence drive is leading the Baltic republic to
catastrophe, but denied that the Kremlin had imposed a total
economic blockade. In Vilnius, officials reaffirmed their
secessionist stand and sent the Soviet premier a list of
items that Lithuania may cease supplying to Soviet industry.
                                                                                                       

   The White House is moving to curtail planned investment
and trade assistance to the Soviet Union in the wake of
Moscow's efforts to crush Lithuania's independence bid, Bush
administration officials said.
   ---
   Voters in Croatia cast ballots in the Yugoslav republic's
first free multiparty elections since before World War II.
The Communists, who have ruled for 45 years, were facing a
challenge from a center-right coalition and a nationalist
party with separatist leanings. Neighboring Slovenians also
voted in elections to choose a regional president.
   ---
   Pope John Paul II announced plans to convene an
unprecedented meeting of Europe's bishops to discuss the
Roman Catholic Church's role on the Continent after the
collapse of Communist governments. The pontiff, who also
intends to visit Cuba in December, made his remarks at the
conclusion of a two-day visit to Czechoslovakia.
   ---
   Nigeria's military government said it crushed a coup
attempt after heavy fighting against rebel troops in Lagos.
The rebellion was launched by junior officers seeking the
breakup of the African country's federation of 19 states in
an effort to end Moslem domination. Casualty figures weren't
disclosed.
   ---
   Mandela called for an intensified armed struggle against
South Africa's white minority government to spur talks to end
apartheid. Speaking in Transkei, the black nationalist also
said he would appeal for tougher anti-apartheid curbs when he
meets with Britain's Thatcher, probably July 6.
   ---
   Israel acknowledged that it had secretly co-financed a
Jewish settlement in the Christian quarter of Jerusalem's
walled Old City, leasing a building owned by the Greek
Orthodox Church through a Panamanian company. Israel said it
paid $1.8 million toward the settlement of 150 Jews, which
sparked strikes and violent protests.
   ---
   Solidarity urged Poland to accelerate the pace of
political and economic restructuring. In a resolution,
approved at a national congress in Gdansk, the trade union
also demanded new elections by early 1991 to remove Communist
holdovers from office.
   ---
   China's Premier Li is scheduled to travel today to the
Soviet Union for talks aimed at solidifying recently restored
ties between the two Communist nations. Moscow and Beijing
are expected to reach agreement on troop withdrawals along
the Sino-Soviet border during the trip by Li, the most senior
Chinese official to visit Moscow since 1964.
   ---
   India's Prime Minister Singh warned Pakistan against
fomenting trouble on the border. He made his statements
following a clash Saturday between Indian and Pakistani
troops in the disputed region of Kashmir, where Moslem
separatists have been waging a pro-independence campaign.
   ---
   Died: Erte, 97, Russian-born artist known for his art deco
painting, sculpture and theatrical design, Saturday, in
Paris.
</TEXT>
