   Transatlantic Holdings
   To Make Initial Offer
   Of Shares to Public
</HL>
<DATE>
04/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14
</SO>
<CO>
   AIG
</CO>
<IN>
INITIAL STOCK OFFERINGS (INI)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Transatlantic Holdings Inc., a property and
casualty reinsurance company whose major shareholder is
American International Group Inc., said it plans an initial
public offering.
   Transatlantic said it plans to sell up to 6.9 million
common shares, including overallotments to underwriters, to
raise a maximum $186.3 million at the proposed offering price
of $27 a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   AIG, which owns approximately 41% of the company, isn't
selling any shares. Of the offering, 4.8 million shares will
be offered in the U.S., managed by Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., and
1.2 million shares outside the U.S., managed by Goldman Sachs
International Ltd.
   According to the filing, Transatlantic had net income in
1989 of $55.7 million, or $2.44 a share; it had total assets
of $1.73 billion at year end.
   The shares are being sold by a group of insurance
companies, most of whom are reducing their holdings by half;
Transatlantic Holdings will receive none of the funds from
the offering.
