<DOCNO>
WSJ900423-0025
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900423-0025.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
04/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   MICHAEL MILKEN AGREED to plead guilty to six felony counts
and to pay $600 million in fines and restitution, the largest
criminal settlement ever. Friday's decision by Drexel's
former junk-bond chief came just before a grand jury was to
indict him on insider trading, bribery and other charges.
It's unclear how much Milken will cooperate with federal
investigators in implicating others.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Far West Financial became the latest big California thrift
to run into financial problems. The S&amp;L posted a $46.1
million loss for 1989 due to writedowns of its junk bonds.
Far West now must raise at least $117 million in capital or
risk a federal takeover.
   ---
   Avon's accord to sell its 60% stake in Avon Japan to a
Tokyo company for $450 million has apparently collapsed. The
failed sale was viewed as a setback for Avon management,
which was going to use the cash to help pay down its $695.9
million debt.
   ---
   First Chicago's profit tumbled 45% in the first quarter,
as expected, mostly due to bad real-estate loans. The bank
denied it improperly told analysts about the problems before
broadly disclosing the information.
   ---
   The slumping bond market is bracing for more blows that
are likely to drive down prices and boost yields further over
the next few weeks. Stocks also are likely to weaken.
                                                                                                       

   Fed Vice Chairman Manuel Johnson said he sees signs of a
pickup in the economy, though inflation remains a threat. His
comments suggest the Fed may favor higher rates.
   ---
   Deficit-reduction talks between the White House and
Congress are "highly likely" to begin within a month, Budget
Director Darman said. Obstacles to an accord are likely to be
defense cuts, taxes and curbing growth in entitlement
programs.
   ---
   Norton's stock rose $2 Friday, to $77.50, after the
Massachusetts abrasives maker said an unidentified bidder had
expressed interest in topping BTR's offer of $75 a share, or
$1.64 billion. BTR is waging a proxy fight to force Norton to
accept the bid.
   ---
   Merck proposed to make its prescription drugs available at
lower prices to Medicaid patients. But it isn't clear that
the plan will deflect federal and state pressure to force the
drug industry to bring down prices.
   ---
   CrossLand Savings posted a $136.5 million quarterly loss
and a doubling of problem assets, worsening its already
severe shortage of capital.
   ---
   GTE agreed to buy cellular phone operations in the
Southeast U.S. from Providence Journal for $710 million,
tightening the telephone industry's grip on cellular
communications.
   ---
   McDonnell Douglas posted a 98% drop in quarterly earnings,
while operating results rose meagerly.
   ---
   Toronto's Reichmann family proposed a reshuffling of
energy assets that would create Canada's biggest domestically
owned oil producer. It also would establish Canada's main oil
pipeline as a separate company.
   ---
   Nigeria told bank creditors it will unilaterally cut
interest payments on $5.4 billion of foreign debt from May 1.
The country, an OPEC member, has been hurt by the slide in
oil prices.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 174,260,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2695.95, off 15.99; transportation 1154.87, off 5.69;
utilities 208.19, off 3.14.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3236.62, off
24.24.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.93, off 0.01;
spot index 136.01, up 0.32.
   Dollar: 157.45 yen, up 0.25; 1.6875 marks, off 0.0009.
