<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   New Zealand's System
   Couldn't Deliver Here
</HL>
<DATE>
04/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<GV>
POSTAL SERVICE (POS)
</GV>
<LP>
   The New Zealand experiment in free enterprise for the mail
sounds attractive as John Crutcher described it in his March
8 editorial-page article. Unfortunately, in order to make his
case, he left out quite a few facts that would cause the
American people to say "no way in the USA."
   Yes, in the first year of "corporatization" an enormous
profit was shown (equal to about $10 billion if applied to
our volume). But the profit was accomplished by the
following: a 33% increase in the price of a first-class
stamp; a reduction in the number of post offices from 1,200
nationwide to 894 nationwide -- with further reductions this
year to just 340; establishment of a higher-priced mail
service called Fast Post, offering next-day service anywhere
in New Zealand for twice the new first-class rate; a one-time
profit from the sale of former postal property.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Recognizing that New Zealand, with a maximum distance of
600 miles between any two points and a population just 1.5%
that of the U.S., is so different from us that comparisons
are difficult, the fact is that service was reduced, except
for those who wanted to pay 166% more. Local post offices,
postal service and even community identity were decimated. We
have 40,000 post offices in the U.S.; as a businessman I
easily could identify for you which of those would be closed
by a business seeking only to maximize profit. The number
would be well over 10,000 post offices. Is this what the
American people want?
   The result in New Zealand is that the government still
owns the post office; that the number of post offices will
have been reduced by more than 70%; and that service has
decreased except for those willing to pay 166% more for
postage. This is not a model for this country.
   Anthony M. Frank
   Postmaster General
   Washington
   ---
   I agree wholeheartedly with the premise in Mr. Crutcher's
article. I would like to know, however, how he arrived at his
compensation figure of $42,000 a year including benefits.
Starting postal-service wages are currently $11 an hour,
without benefits. The U.S. postal carrier is at the top of
the range after 15 years and is paid $30,000. To reach the
$42,000 level, his benefits package would have to be 40%.
Even with government largess, I have trouble believing
benefits are 40% of wages. Even if they were, the average,
semi-skilled employee would not be paid $42,000.
   Also, comparing New Zealand wages of $15,000 with U.S.
wages is hardly appropriate. I visited New Zealand in 1986
and I would say it's well behind the U.S. in standard of
living.
   Obviously, United Parcel Service has demonstrated it can
be successful at delivering packages, so privatizing the
Postal Service probably would result in better service at a
cheaper cost. In the meantime, however, eliminating Saturday
delivery to residences as well as charging higher postage to
bulk mailers would cut costs tremendously. Bulk mailers would
not send three or more copies of the same catalog in one
month if they couldn't mail them so cheaply. There is no mail
delivered to a residence on Saturday that couldn't wait until
Monday.
   E.H. Melendres
   Cathedral City, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900423-0016
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900423-0016.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy -- Tracking the Economy:
   GNP Annual Growth Rate for 1st Period
   Seen Doubling Forecasts, to About 2.5%
   ----
   By Pamela Sebastian
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Now that it's over, the first quarter looks
twice as strong as most folks thought it would at the start.
   The consensus view estimates an annual growth rate of
about 2.5% in real gross national product for the quarter, up
from the 1% growth outlook that prevailed in January,
according to MMS International, a unit of McGraw-Hill Inc.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The government takes its first stab at estimating GNP in a
report Friday. Real GNP is the inflation-adjusted value of
the nation's output of goods and services. The data also are
expected to show that inflation heated up in the quarter. And
more inflationary timber is expected from tomorrow's report
on the first-quarter employment cost index. The week's only
other indicator, March durable goods orders, is still thought
to be on the rebound, after January's plunge.
   Economists generally have been raising their GNP
forecasts, because of the unpredictable weather, imperfect
statistics, inventory swings, and some plain old
miscalculations.
   Some, at least, are good-humored about taking the blame.
"I don't usually make a habit of comparing what I say at the
beginning of the quarter to what I say at the end," Robert
Dederick, chief economist of Northern Trust Co. in Chicago,
said. "It just depresses me." As many of his counterparts
did, Mr. Dederick in January predicted 1% growth. "I'm now
saying 2% to 2.5%," he said.
   "Business's fixed investment is higher than we thought. So
is residential construction," Mr. Dederick said, noting two
areas boosted by unseasonably mild January weather. He said
better-than-expected exports helped the trade deficit and
added strength to the quarter.
   Asked about his change-of-heart estimate, Michael Moran,
economist at Daiwa Securities America Inc., said: "Oh, boy.
It's much stronger than I had at the beginning of the
quarter." He now expects growth of 2.3% for the quarter, up
from the 1% to 1.5% he forecast at the start of the period.
GNP grew at an annual rate of 1.1% in the 1989 fourth
quarter.
   Two improved areas that surprised Mr. Moran the most in
the first quarter: the trade-sector improvement and
fixed-investment spending. Besides the benefits of mild
weather, he noted that overall "demand was just a bit more
robust than we thought was likely."
   While the first quarter may have been stronger than they
thought, many economists said the growth pace won't hold.
   Donald Fine, chief economist at Chase Manhattan Bank, New
York, raised his first-quarter estimate to 2.5% from around
1%. But he doesn't expect the pace to continue in the months
ahead. "I think capital spending will slip off," he said.
"Construction will definitely fall off. And we don't know if
trade will get much better." On the other side, Mr. Fine
said, auto output is likely to be stronger in the second
quarter than in the first. "But that's quarterly auto
catch-up," he said.
   Many economists, including Robert Chandross at Lloyds
Bank, are sticking to their full-year forecasts but are
reshuffling the quarters. "Basically, there'll be a little
more in the first quarter and a little less in the second,"
he said. "I'm still looking for {a} 2%" annual growth rate
from the 1989 fourth quarter to this year's fourth quarter.
   An inflation measure of the GNP report known as the
implicit price deflator is expected to have risen at a 5.5%
annual rate for the quarter. Allen Sinai, Boston Co.'s chief
economist, expects to see "uncomfortably strong inflation"
for the first quarter, with the implicit deflator as high as
6%.
   The first-quarter employment cost index is expected to add
to inflationary fears, with an increase of about 5.5% to 6%
on a year-to-year basis. Economists pointed out that part of
the rise in employment cost results from Social Security
payment increases that took effect in January.
   Expectations for tomorrow's report on March durable goods
orders are typically scattered. Estimates range from a
decline of 1.2% to an increase of 5.1%, with the median view
a rise of 2%, according to MMS. Most economists expect some
kind of increase in durable goods, as orders continue to
rebound from January's sharp 10.5% plunge.
   ---
